    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3737374440" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3737374440" />
    <a title="Taddow" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7060018-taddow"><img alt="Taddow" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349562011p2/7060018.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3737374440?book_show_action=true">Jan 08, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Taddow" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Taddow" href="/user/show/7060018-taddow">Taddow</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3737374440" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3592026409872783230">I’m actually surprised that it took me this long to read this book. I remember people talking about it when it first came out and I was no stranger to TSR published novels, but for whatever reason I didn’t read it until now. It was only relatively recently that I read the first three novels of the Drizzt’ Do’Urden series and I enjoyed them quite a bit. I also know those novels were actually written after this novel and perhaps that contributed to my enjoyment of them more so than this one. Not t</span>
  <span id="freeText3592026409872783230" style="display:none">I’m actually surprised that it took me this long to read this book. I remember people talking about it when it first came out and I was no stranger to TSR published novels, but for whatever reason I didn’t read it until now. It was only relatively recently that I read the first three novels of the Drizzt’ Do’Urden series and I enjoyed them quite a bit. I also know those novels were actually written after this novel and perhaps that contributed to my enjoyment of them more so than this one. Not that this was a bad novel, I enjoyed it, but I found more refinement in the presentation of Drizzt’s character in the first three novels (which makes sense since he’s the main focus of those novels). In this novel Drizzt is a main character, but he holds that place with several others. This isn’t bad for reading, but I think it contributed to why I enjoyed the first three novels more- there’s a deeper look at how the Drow felt about his place in a world that wasn’t his normal for his race and the constant conflict and reconciliation of choosing that place. <br /><br />Another thing that bothered me a bit was the myriad of coincidences that occurred to “win the day.” I know this happens a lot, especially in these types of fantasy novels, and I don’t mind them (I actually enjoy them if there is some foreshadowing or interesting twist that makes sense in hindsight), but without giving away spoilers, there were several moments in the book where things could go terribly wrong but didn’t because…well, of course you have that thing that can do this, or you do this and that’s exactly what caused this other thing to happen that saved you from that. There was just a little too much of it for me. If I would have read this book when it first came out, I’m sure I would have been dazzled by the story, but my age has changed my expectations a bit.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3592026409872783230" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


